    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided prospectus preamble and financial statement notes, the acquisitions of xAI and X Holdings were accounted for as **reorganizations of entities under common control** because Elon Musk held a controlling financial and majority voting interest in SpaceX, xAI, and X prior to the mergers. As a result, all historical intercompany transactions between SpaceX, xAI, and X were eliminated in consolidation. \n\nHowever, the newly consolidated structure maintains extensive, ongoing related-party relationships and transactions with external entities affiliated with Elon Musk, SpaceX board members, and underwriters. \n\nHere is the retrieved disclosure of related-party relationships and transactions within the consolidated structure:\n\n### 1. Elon Musk and Affiliated Entities\nElon Musk serves as the Founder, CEO, CTO, and Chairman of SpaceX, while simultaneously holding leadership and ownership roles in several other ventures that transact with the consolidated company.\n\n*   **Tesla, Inc.** (Musk is CEO, Technoking, director, and ~20% shareholder; Tesla owns <1.0% of SpaceX Class A stock):\n    *   **Equipment & Vehicle Purchases:** The company purchased massive amounts of energy and vehicle products from Tesla, including Megapack products ($191M in 2024; $506M in 2025; $34M in Q1 2026) and Cybertrucks ($131M in 2025), recorded in Property, Plant, and Equipment.\n    *   **Commercial, Licensing & Support Agreements:** SpaceX obtained goods/services from Tesla ($11M in 2023; $4M in 2024; $144M in 2025). xAI also obtained goods/services ($191M in 2024; $506M in 2025) and recognized minor revenue from Tesla.\n    *   **Advertising:** Tesla purchased advertising on the X platform ($0.5M in 2024; $4M in 2025).\n    *   **Aircraft Usage:** SpaceX invoiced Tesla for the use of SpaceX-owned aircraft by Musk and Tesla personnel ($1M in 2023; $1M in 2024; $2M in 2025).\n    *   **Strategic Investment:** In January 2026, Tesla agreed to invest **$2,000 million** in xAI Series E Preferred Stock. Following the xAI Merger, this right converted into SpaceX Class A Common Stock, resulting in the issuance of **3.8 million shares** to Tesla in March 2026.\n*   **The Boring Company** (Infrastructure company founded by Musk):\n    *   **Leases & Construction:** X leases office space from a Boring Company subsidiary ($0.1M in 2024; $1M in 2025). Additionally, SpaceX incurred $1M in 2025 for the construction of tunnels in Bastrop, Texas.\n*   **Musk Industries LLC** (Owned by Musk):\n    *   **Real Estate Lease:** xAI leases real property from this entity ($0.5M in 2024; $2M in 2025; $0.2M in early 2026).\n*   **Musk-Owned Security Company:**\n    *   **Security Services:** SpaceX pays a security company organized to protect Musk, including during his SpaceX duties ($2M in 2023; $3M in 2024; $4M in 2025; $1M in early 2026).\n*   **Elon Musk Trust:**\n    *   **Share Repurchases:** In 2025, Musk\'s trust purchased **$1,421 million** of common stock from current and former employees.\n\n### 2. Antonio J. Gracias and Valor Equity Partners\nAntonio J. Gracias is a member of the SpaceX Board of Directors and the founder, CEO, and CIO of Valor Equity Partners ("Valor").\n*   **Massive AI Infrastructure Leases (Failed Sale-Leasebacks):** xAI subsidiaries entered into three major equipment lease agreements with Valor for AI computing hardware. The aggregate cash payments over the life of these leases are staggering: **$6,986 million**, **$6,633 million**, and **$6,587 million** (guaranteed by SpaceX). \n    *   *Accounting Treatment:* These were deemed "failed sale-leaseback transactions." As of March 31, 2026, the company recorded **$1,121 million** in current debt and **$7,920 million** in non-current debt on the consolidated balance sheet related to these Valor agreements, alongside $186 million in interest expense for Q1 2026.\n*   **X API Services:** X received payments from Valor for API services ($1M in 2024; $1M in 2025).\n\n### 3. Other Directors and Executive Officers\n*   **Corporate Aircraft:** Through its subsidiary Falcon Landing, LLC, SpaceX owns and operates three aircraft specifically for use by its directors and executive officers (specific financial amounts for this bullet are cut off in the source text, but the relationship is formally disclosed).\n\n### 4. Underwriters and Financial Affiliates\nThe prospectus discloses potential conflicts of interest regarding the financial institutions underwriting the offering, as they are deeply embedded in the company\'s financial and advisory structure:\n*   **Advisory Roles:** Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC advised SpaceX in connection with the acquisition of xAI.\n*   **Lending & Credit Facilities:** Affiliates of the underwriters (including Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, BofA, Citigroup, J.P. Morgan, Barclays, Deutsche Bank, RBC, UBS, and Wells Fargo) serve as lenders, administrative agents, or co-agents under the **SpaceX Bridge Loan** and the **SpaceX Credit Facility**. \n\n*(Note: Because the xAI and X mergers were common-control reorganizations, any historical transactions that occurred strictly between SpaceX, xAI, and X prior to the mergers—such as internal funding or shared services—have been entirely eliminated in the consolidated financial statements and are not presented as external related-party transactions.)*',
