    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided S-1 filing excerpts, here is the detailed extraction of the sections concerning **Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions**, **Board Member Relationships**, and **Underwriter Conflicts of Interest**.\n\n### 1. Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions\nThe company has established a written policy requiring the audit committee to review and approve any "related person transaction" exceeding **$120,000** involving directors, executive officers, >5% shareholders, or their immediate family members. Following the February 2026 xAI Merger, this section also encompasses ongoing agreements originally entered into by xAI or X Holdings.\n\n**Transactions with Elon Musk and Affiliated Entities:**\n*   **Tesla, Inc.:** \n    *   Tesla beneficially owns 18,990,195 shares of Class A common stock (less than 1.0% post-offering).\n    *   SpaceX maintains commercial, licensing, and support agreements with Tesla on arm\'s-length terms. \n    *   As of December 31, 2025, the Company purchased **$506 million** in Megapack products and **$131 million** in Cybertrucks at MSRP from Tesla for use in property, plant, and equipment.\n*   **The Boring Company:** \n    *   X entered into an office space lease with a Boring Company subsidiary (payments of $0.1M in 2024, $1M in 2025, and $0.1M in early 2026). \n    *   SpaceX incurred **$1 million** in 2025 for tunnel construction by The Boring Company in Bastrop, Texas.\n*   **Musk Industries LLC:** xAI leases real property from this Musk-owned entity ($0.5M in 2024, $2M in 2025, $0.2M in early 2026).\n*   **Security Services:** SpaceX utilizes a Musk-owned security company for personal and corporate security services, incurring expenses of $2M (2023), $3M (2024), $4M (2025), and $1M (early 2026).\n\n### 2. Board Member Relationships & Director Conflicts\nThe filing highlights specific financial ties and potential competitive conflicts involving members of the board of directors:\n\n*   **Antonio J. Gracias & Valor Equity Partners:** \n    *   Antonio J. Gracias, a company director, is the Founder, CEO, and CIO of Valor Equity Partners.\n    *   Certain subsidiaries (including CTC/xAI) entered into AI infrastructure hardware equipment lease agreements with Valor. \n    *   These were accounted for as **failed sale-leaseback transactions**. As of March 31, 2026, the Company recorded **$1,121 million** in current debt, **$7,920 million** in non-current debt, and **$186 million** in interest expenses related to these leases.\n*   **Donald Harrison:** The board noted that Harrison is employed by an organization that does business with the Company, though the transaction amounts fell below the materiality thresholds (greater of $200,000 or 5% of revenue).\n*   **Competitive Conflicts & Corporate Opportunities:** Directors and key employees may serve on the boards of or have financial relationships with competing space, AI, or satellite communications ventures. Furthermore, the company\'s charter explicitly **renounces certain corporate opportunities** presented to Elon Musk and specific directors, meaning they have no duty to present these outside opportunities to the Company.\n\n### 3. Underwriter Conflicts of Interest\nThe underwriting syndicate comprises full-service financial institutions with deep, pre-existing financial and advisory ties to the Company and its affiliates, creating potential conflicts of interest:\n\n*   **Advisory Roles:** **Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC** specifically advised the Company in connection with the acquisition of xAI.\n*   **Lending & Credit Facilities:** Affiliates of the underwriters are heavily entrenched in the Company\'s debt structure. \n    *   *SpaceX Bridge Loan:* Affiliates of Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, BofA, Citigroup, J.P. Morgan, Barclays, Deutsche Bank, RBC, UBS, and Wells Fargo serve as lenders or administrative agents.\n    *   *SpaceX Credit Facility:* Affiliates of BofA, Citigroup, Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, Barclays, Deutsche Bank, Wells Fargo, RBC, and UBS serve as lenders.\n*   **Directed Share Program (DSP):** At the Company\'s request, underwriters reserved a percentage of the IPO shares for sale to employees, management, business partners, and **friends and family of management**. Shares purchased through the DSP are **exempt from standard lock-up restrictions**, meaning these insiders can sell immediately, reducing the public float and presenting a structural conflict of interest regarding IPO allocation.\n\n### 4. Governance & Control Context\n*   **Controlled Company Status:** Post-IPO, Elon Musk will hold majority voting power via Class B common stock. The Company will rely on "controlled company" exemptions under Nasdaq rules, bypassing certain independent board and committee requirements.\n*   **Investors\' Rights Agreement:** Certain existing shareholders (covered under the Related Person Transactions section) hold contractual rights to demand registration of their shares, allowing them to bypass Rule 144 holding periods and potentially flood the market with stock post-lock-up.',
