2026-06-09 22:33:41,614 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Related-Party Relationships Within the Consolidated SpaceX Structure (Post-Merger)\n\nFollowing the xAI Merger (February 2, 2026) and the X Merger (March 28, 2025), the S-1 identifies a web of related-party relationships spanning Elon Musk\'s affiliated entities, board members, and underwriting institutions. These are detailed primarily in the section titled **"Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions"** and in **Note 1 (Nature of Business)** and **Note 2 (Summary of Significant Accounting Policies)** of the consolidated financial statements.\n\n---\n\n### 1. Elon Musk and Affiliated External Entities\n\nElon Musk serves as Founder, CEO, CTO, and Chairman of SpaceX while simultaneously holding leadership and ownership roles in several other ventures that transact with the consolidated entity:\n\n| Related Party | Relationship | Key Transactions |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tesla, Inc.** | Musk is CEO, Technoking, director, ~20% shareholder; Tesla owns <1.0% of SpaceX Class A stock | Megapack purchases ($191M in 2024; $506M in 2025; $34M in Q1 2026); Cybertruck purchases ($131M in 2025); commercial/licensing/support services ($11M in 2023; $4M in 2024; $144M in 2025 from SpaceX; $191M in 2024; $506M in 2025 from xAI); Tesla advertising on X ($0.5M in 2024; $4M in 2025); aircraft usage invoiced to Tesla ($1M in 2023; $1M in 2024; $2M in 2025); Tesla\'s $2,000M investment in xAI Series E (converted to 3.8M shares of SpaceX Class A in March 2026) |\n| **The Boring Company** | Infrastructure company founded by Musk | X leases office space from a Boring Company subsidiary ($0.1M in 2024; $1M in 2025; $0.1M in early 2026); SpaceX incurred $1M in 2025 for tunnel construction in Bastrop, Texas |\n| **Musk Industries LLC** | Owned by Musk | xAI leases real property ($0.5M in 2024; $2M in 2025; $0.2M in early 2026) |\n| **Musk-Owned Security Company** | Organized to protect Musk | SpaceX pays for security services including during SpaceX duties ($2M in 2023; $3M in 2024; $4M in 2025; $1M in early 2026) |\n| **Elon Musk Trust** | Controlled by Musk | Purchased $1,421M of common stock from current and former employees in 2025 |\n\n### 2. Antonio J. Gracias and Valor Equity Partners\n\nAntonio J. Gracias is a SpaceX board member and the Founder, CEO, and CIO of Valor Equity Partners. This relationship generates the single largest related-party financial exposure in the filing:\n\n- **AI Infrastructure Equipment Leases (Failed Sale-Leasebacks):** xAI subsidiaries (including CTC) entered into three major computing equipment lease agreements with Valor, guaranteed by SpaceX. Aggregate cash payment obligations over the life of the leases total:\n  - First lease: **$6,986 million**\n  - Second lease: **$6,633 million**\n  - Third lease: **$6,587 million**\n- These were accounted for as **failed sale-leaseback transactions**, recorded as debt rather than operating leases. As of March 31, 2026: **$1,121 million** current debt and **$7,920 million** non-current debt on the consolidated balance sheet, with **$186 million** in interest expense for Q1 2026 alone.\n- Cash payments already made: $885M in 2025 and $857M from January 1 through February 28, 2026.\n- **X API Services:** X received minor payments from Valor for API services ($1M in 2024; $1M in 2025; $0.1M in early 2026).\n\n### 3. Other Directors and Executive Officers\n\n- **Donald Harrison:** Employed by an organization that does business with the Company, though transaction amounts fell below the materiality threshold (greater of $200,000 or 5% of revenue).\n- **Corporate Aircraft:** Through subsidiary Falcon Landing, LLC, SpaceX owns and operates three aircraft for use by directors and executive officers.\n- **Competitive Conflicts:** The charter explicitly renounces certain corporate opportunities presented to Musk and specific directors, meaning they have no duty to present outside opportunities to the Company.\n\n### 4. Underwriters and Financial Affiliates\n\n- **Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC** advised SpaceX on the xAI acquisition.\n- Affiliates of Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, BofA, Citigroup, J.P. Morgan, Barclays, Deutsche Bank, RBC, UBS, and Wells Fargo serve as lenders or agents under both the **SpaceX Bridge Loan** and the **SpaceX Credit Facility**.\n- A **Directed Share Program** reserves IPO shares for employees, management, business partners, and friends/family of management, exempt from standard lock-up restrictions.\n\n---\n\n## Pre-Merger Intercompany Activity: Where the Filing Discusses It\n\nThe filing **does not disclose specific details, amounts, or business descriptions of pre-merger intercompany transactions** between SpaceX, xAI, and X Holdings. Instead, it addresses their elimination in the following locations:\n\n### Location 1: Prospectus Preamble / Summary Historical Financial Data\nThe preamble states:\n> *"The consolidated financial statements of SpaceX have been retrospectively recast for all periods presented to include (i) the historical results of X.AI Holdings Corp., which was acquired by SpaceX, effective February 2, 2026 (the \'xAI Merger\'), and X Holdings Corp. (\'X Holdings\'), which was acquired by xAI, effective March 28, 2025 (the \'X Merger\'), because these transactions were between entities under common control..."*\n\n### Location 2: Note 1 — Nature of Business (Consolidated Financial Statements)\nThis is the most explicit discussion. The filing states:\n> *"The Mergers have been accounted for as reorganizations of entities under common control as Mr. Elon Musk had a controlling financial interest in the Company, xAI and X through his majority voting interest in each such entity during the periods presented in these consolidated financial statements. The Company\'s consolidated financial statements have been prepared to reflect the retrospective combination of the net assets of the entities at their historical carrying amounts for all periods presented. No new goodwill or other intangible assets have been recorded and **all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation**."*\n\nThe note further clarifies that this presentation constitutes a **change in reporting entity**, with capital stock and shareholders\' equity for all periods reflecting a continuation of historical SpaceX equity combined with X and xAI equity, adjusted by the respective exchange ratios.\n\n### Location 3: Note 2 — Summary of Significant Accounting Policies\nThe standard consolidation policy states:\n> *"The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of the Company and its wholly owned subsidiaries. All intercompany balances and transactions have been eliminated in consolidation."*\n\n### Key Analytical Takeaway\n\nBecause the mergers were common-control reorganizations (not arm\'s-length acquisitions), **all pre-merger transactions between SpaceX, xAI, and X Holdings were eliminated** in the retrospectively recast financial statements. The filing does not break out or quantify what those internal transactions were — only that they have been fully eliminated. Consequently, no period in the financial statements reflects standalone SpaceX operations; every historical period presents the combined entity as if the three companies had always been consolidated. This is analytically material because it means investors cannot isolate SpaceX\'s pre-merger standalone financial performance from the S-1.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (Filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
