uties ($2M in 2023; $3M in 2024; $4M in 2025; $1M in early 2026) |\n| **Elon Musk Trust** | Controlled by Musk | Purchased $1,421M of common stock from current and former employees in 2025 |\n\n### 2. Antonio J. Gracias and Valor Equity Partners\n\nAntonio J. Gracias is a SpaceX board member and the Founder, CEO, and CIO of Valor Equity Partners. This relationship generates the single largest related-party financial exposure in the filing:\n\n- **AI Infrastructure Equipment Leases (Failed Sale-Leasebacks):** xAI subsidiaries (including CTC) entered into three major computing equipment lease agreements with Valor, guaranteed by SpaceX. Aggregate cash payment obligations over the life of the leases total:\n  - First lease: **$6,986 million**\n  - Second lease: **$6,633 million**\n  - Third lease: **$6,587 million**\n- These were accounted for as **failed sale-leaseback transactions**, recorded as debt rather than operating leases. As of March 31, 2026: **$1,121 million** current debt and **$7,920 million** non-current debt on the consolidated balance sheet, with **$186 million** in interest expense for Q1 2026 alone.\n- Cash payments already made: $885M in 2025 and $857M from January 1 through February 28, 2026.\n- **X API Services:** X received minor payments from Valor for API services ($1M in 2024; $1M in 2025; $0.1M in early 2026).\n\n### 3. Other Directors and Executive Officers\n\n- **Donald Harrison:** Employed by an organization that does business with the Company, though transaction amounts fell below the materiality threshold (greater of $200,000 or 5% of revenue).\n- **Corporate Aircraft:** Through subsidiary Falcon Landing, LLC, SpaceX owns and operates three aircraft for use by directors and executive officers.\n- **Competitive Conflicts:** The charter explicitly renounces certain corporate opportunities presented to Musk and specific directors, meaning they have no duty to present outside opportunities to the Company.\n\n### 4. Underwriters and Financial